Author: Sanamyan, Sanamyan, McDaniel, Martynov, Korshunova & Bocharova, 2019
(Müller, 1776)
Critical Notes: under review - note in WoRMS that this is properly only an Atlantic species and should be grebelnyi

Dr. Gary Williams is still grappling with the official naming of this species; "both the 'Gulf Island soft coral' and the 'Race Rocks/Browning Passage/Weynton Passage soft coral' are in the genus Alcyonium. But they are genetically different and await sorting out taxonomically." (Neil McDaniel pers. comm. 2019)

Claudia Mills: "I think that there are several Euphysas in the area. I think 40 years ago that I was aware of one with only three tentacles and one with four tentacles. Now I wonder if the ones that I see (only) in June are different from the ones that I see in September. There is also an interstitial one - which I’ll have to look up. But mostly I think that we don’t know. I before believed in historical knowledge about this genus, but I am no longer sure about it. Am I getting old, or do I just not believe the old stories? I don’t think that anyone has studied this genus carefully here, actually." The differences are apparently in the young specimens: E. japonica (one record in Vancouver, but mostly in Japan, and I’m guessing the one here may well be genetically not E. japonica, but that is unprovable right now) - has four tentacles, all alike, including in the youngest stages. E. flammea has four alike tentacles as an adult, but they develop successively - it is released with only one tentacle. E. tentaculata (which may well be an Arctic species) is said to have one long tentacle, two half as long, and one bulb without tentacles. 

The reason that I’ve settled on calling them just Euphysa sp. is that one mostly sees the adult. There is also another species of Euphysa described only as an interstitial polyp on San Juan Island (I think it is Euphysa ruthae), but which probably makes medusae. I’ve noticed that I see Euphysa medusae both in the spring and in the fall (rarely if ever in the summer) - just guessing that those could be two different species. We just don’t know enough. As a reference, I’m using Kramp, P.L. (1961). Medusae of the World. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, Volume 40: 1-468.

Author: Fraser, 1922
Critical Notes: Andy Lamb: "With respect to Hydractinia sp, vs Hydractinia cf. laevispina -- our data base and Jensen et al, 2018 use the former"

Author: (Bonnevie, 1898)
Critical Notes: Schuchertinia allmani grows on the shells of hermit crabs "in general" and its polyps are much larger. Lee Newman's attached image demonstrates. Clavactinia serrata apparently only grows upon the shells carried by the splendid hermit Labidochirus splendens and its polyps are very small and usually not obvious to the naked eye. Accepted spelling in WoRMS is Schuchertinia allmanii

Author: (Murbach and Shearer, 1902)
Critical Notes: Andy et al. report Aequorea sp.; Wyatt Patry, Senior Aquarist at the Monterey Bay Aquarium, reports that A. victoria is our native species, named nearby; whereas A. forskalea is native to Europe or the East Coast.  Sarah Abboud's recent molecular analysis of all the Aequorea on the west coast showed they belonged to a 'victoria' clade with many potential species/sub-species within. This is a species complex, though Sarah has not published or renamed anything. Claudia's website has all the literature listed.

Author: (Eschscholtz, 1829)
Critical Notes: Recorded as Diphyes appendiculata in CMN catalogue; Henry Choong: "Chelophyes appendiculata (Eschscholtz, 1829) has been reported from the Pacific as well as the Atlantic. Diphyes appendiculata Eschscholtz, 1829 is the original name. I'm not sure when Anita collected the specimen you mention, but it couldn't have been 1928, as she was born in 1929. I looked at the CMN record, but the collection date is incorrect. Nevertheless, I have seen warm-water species drift to our coast, so it is possible."
